# Deployment URL Management Standards

## Critical Rule: Never Document URLs Until Deployed

**⚠️ NEVER add deployment URLs to README, package.json, or GitHub About until the service is actually deployed and verified working.**

This prevents broken links and confusion for users.

## Deployment Status Documentation

### Use Deployment Badges

Always use status badges to show what's actually deployed:

```markdown
## 🚀 Deployment Status

| Service | Status | URL |
|---------|--------|-----|
| **Dashboard** | [![Cloudflare Pages](https://img.shields.io/badge/Cloudflare-Deployed-orange?logo=cloudflare)](https://telegram-affiliate-dashboard.pages.dev) | [telegram-affiliate-dashboard.pages.dev](https://telegram-affiliate-dashboard.pages.dev) |
| **API** | [![Cloudflare Workers](https://img.shields.io/badge/Cloudflare-Deployed-orange?logo=cloudflare)](https://api.example.com) | [api.example.com](https://api.example.com) |
| **Bot** | [![Telegram](https://img.shields.io/badge/Telegram-Running-blue?logo=telegram)](https://t.me/yourbot) | [@yourbot](https://t.me/yourbot) |
```

**Benefits:**
- Users know what's actually live
- No broken links
- Clear deployment status
- Professional appearance

### Deployment Checklist

Before adding a URL to any documentation:

- [ ] Service is deployed and accessible
- [ ] URL returns 200 OK (not 404 or 502)
- [ ] DNS is configured (if using custom domain)
- [ ] SSL certificate is valid
- [ ] CI/CD is set up for automatic deployments
- [ ] Deployment badge is added to README
- [ ] URL is added to package.json `homepage` field
- [ ] GitHub About is updated with verified URL

## GitHub Repository About Settings

### Homepage Field Rules

```json
// package.json
{
  // ❌ DON'T: Add undeployed URLs
  "homepage": "https://my-app.pages.dev"  // Not deployed yet
  
  // ✅ DO: Use GitHub until deployed
  "homepage": "https://github.com/username/repo#readme"
  
  // ✅ DO: Add after deployment is verified
  "homepage": "https://my-app.pages.dev"  // After confirming it works
}
```

### GitHub About Priority

1. **Until deployed:** Use GitHub repo URL
2. **After deployment:** Use production URL
3. **Multiple services:** Use main user-facing URL (dashboard > API)
4. **Custom domain:** Use custom domain, not `.pages.dev`

Example progression:

```
# Phase 1: Development
Homepage: https://github.com/username/telegram-affiliate#readme

# Phase 2: Dashboard Deployed
Homepage: https://telegram-affiliate-dashboard.pages.dev

# Phase 3: Custom Domain
Homepage: https://affiliate.example.com
```

## CI/CD for Automatic Deployments

### Required Workflows

Always set up GitHub Actions for automatic deployments:

**.github/workflows/deploy-dashboard.yml**
```yaml
name: Deploy Dashboard

on:
  push:
    branches: [main]
    paths:
      - 'apps/dashboard/**'

jobs:
  deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: cloudflare/pages-action@v1
        with:
          apiToken: ${{ secrets.CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN }}
          accountId: ${{ secrets.CLOUDFLARE_ACCOUNT_ID }}
          projectName: your-project-name
          directory: dist
```

**.github/workflows/deploy-api.yml**
```yaml
name: Deploy API

on:
  push:
    branches: [main]
    paths:
      - 'apps/api/**'

jobs:
  deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: cloudflare/wrangler-action@v3
        with:
          apiToken: ${{ secrets.CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN }}
```

**Benefits:**
- Automatic deployments on push
- No manual deployment needed
- Always up-to-date
- Less chance of forgetting to deploy

